<br>
    Wizards have tested Spell casting Spec into the ground. It is a flat rate and for a level 60 Wizard it does NOT vary from a level 1 spell to a level 60 spell. Same exact near 10 percent reduction EVERY time. The problem here is that the manabar is RANDOM. It is not the spec but the mana shown thats random. Try this. Cast an expensive spell from a nonspec line and it will be random also. Even from FM every time. Its more dependent on the amount of the spell cost. dependant on your manapool, a 200 mana spell may look like it takes the same mana every time, where a 300 mana spell may take a random amount every time from FM. Its either a bug, or verant specificly has points set on the mana bar once you pass them it has a random amount it visually shows. Most likely set on percentages of FM I think. If a Speced spell that costs 200 mana gives a random lowering on your manba bar try a non spec spell of the SAME cost, or up to 10 percent more, and you will get the same random results. Also FM on the bar does NOT mean you are FM. Most of my tests have shown to be truly FM you need to med aprox 30 to 45 seconds more, depending on mana pool extra regen etc, to get to true FM. So if your hanging around then decide hrm I wanna test this. Cast a spell med to &quot;full&quot; cast agian your mana bar will move down more the second cast because you really have less mana the second time you med to just FM visually. Depending on your mana pool this can be up to 200 mana.<br>
<br>
P.S. one of the ways wizards tested Spec skill is this. This is just one of the ways not the only one used.<br>
<br>
1. Remove all your gear remove all buffs.<br>
2. load up a range of spells all the way to very cheap low level one spells. Choose a testing spell in your spec skill thats pretty cheap say 10 to 20 mana.<br>
3. Cast till absolutly oom use a very cheap spell 3-4 mana as the last casts.<br>
4. REMAIN standing. With no points in mental clar you regen standing at 1 mana a tic. Keep spamm clicking your testing spell, 10-20 mana. as soon as you have regened enough mana to cast it your spell will start going off.<br>
5. Time how long it takes from casting the spell to beeing able to cast it agian. Divide the seconds by 6, there are 6 seconds a tic, and you have how much mana that spell cost.<br>
6. repeate step 4 and 5 untill you have a large enough set to come to a good avrg.  <br>
7. Redo steps 4 and 5 with a higher mana cost spell.<br>
8. chart results.<br>
<br>
Not many people have done the high level spells. Even with the cheap droughts 215 mana takes a long while to regen standing. But a few have done sets of 50 casts and came up with the same numbers as each other so its probably close to acurate. The low mana cost spells have been tested at thousands of casts per person.<br>
<br>
All point to every spell is reduced by apric 10-11 percent on your speced skill other spells are reduced 2-3 percent. not the avrg EVERY spell myself out of 100 casts on a 10 mana spell 97 casts cost 9 mana, 1 cost 10, 2 cost 8. I atribute the 3 non 9 mana casts to miscounts. I was very carefull to time when Tics would happen so I could keep acurate count of them but lag etc I am sure made me miss out on those 3 even though I was on a nice PC with a T1 line. On larger tests, where miss counting one tic has less effect of messing the test up, the results are even more acurate with several people getting tests of 100 casts all at 10-11 percent reduction. Every single cast out of 100. No one out of thousands of test EVER got more then a 13 or 14 percent reductionon a single spell, wich was atributed to bad counting or lag effects. <br>
<br>
Note spells will not cast till you have enough mana to cast the full casting cost. Spec reduction is aplied after mana reqs are met. So if you have a 100 mana spell it will NOT cast till you have 100 mana even if its your main spec and will always cost 90 mana.<br>
